    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\ncmdline abbreviation is not very useful because it replaces stuff anywhere within an cmdine, e.g. `:cabbrev x y` replaces `x` anywhere in the cmdline, thus `:cmd x<space> => :cmd y` \n\nThis leads to all kinds of requests for features that really could just be resolved by a single feature: the ability to properly replace only the `:cmd` part of an interactive cmdline. \n\nUse-cases:\n\n- typos: `:H` => `:h`\n- mapping \"lowercase commands\" to user-defined commands: `:man` => `:Man`\n    - this doesn't affect scripts, only the interactive `:` cmdline.\n- default modifiers: `:te` => `:hor te`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe \"command\" part of an interactive cmdline can be replaced by an abbreviation (without false positives).\n\n`:h abbreviation` describes \"three types of abbreviations\". We could introduce a fourth \"type\", identified by a `:` prefix, e.g. `:cabbrev :man :Man`.\n\n- The \"short\" variants of the command all are recognized without the user needing to explicitly define them.\n- Handles `[range]`, bang (!), and other standard cmdline modifiers.\n\nThus:\n\n- `:cabbrev :grep :& grep` \n    - expands `:gr<space>` to `:& grep<space>`.\n    - expands `:1,2gr<space>` to `:& 1,2grep<space>`.\n    - expands `:echo gr | 1,2gr<space>` to `:echo gr | & 1,2grep<space>`.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "As a reference: 'mini.cmdline' tries to resolve the underlying issue of \"do what I want not what I type\" by the concept of [autocorrection](https://nvim-mini.org/mini.nvim/doc/mini-cmdline.html#minicmdline.config-autocorrect). Basically: detect when a \"word\" has finished typing, infer its completion type, and check if typed words comes from a fixed set of candidates (commands, flags, enums, etc). If not - find the closest and replace. Here are [its tests](https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.nvim/blob/4f6f84a96b076747b736d100388a8d7844771d7d/tests/test_cmdline.lua#L651-L1127) that showcase what it is expected to do.",
